<subSubSection id="189FE0F545F67D1E8DD970454CDFA0C4" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="029CBA30F3C8CDF24FA8BC8365DCDC6A" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B28DD1E32A09ECAB9C0EBA5A56221CBE" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
1) Pileipellis, pileus and lamellar tramae and stipe medullary hyphae embedded in slime matrix; 2) pileipellis either: a) a layer of repent, encrusted hyphae, conspicuously clamped, usually with thickened walls (through gelatinization) and embedded in a slime matrix; or b) well-developed 
<emphasis id="BF888EF82DD0B5029523C2E97B283920" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rameales</emphasis>
-structure; 3) cheilocystidia often absent, when present either clavate to utriform or 
<emphasis id="A04D931E476A4B28ACF64B3D457B58F1" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">siccus</emphasis>
-type broom cell-like; 4) stipes usually less than 1 mm broad but often up to 40 mm long; ratio of pileus breadth to stipe length often large (see 
<taxonomicName id="C2FFBD73662A9A02B6BE8E62CEBD6932" genus="G." lsidName="G. pinophilus" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="pinophilus">
<emphasis id="6413CA2843DDC6AD23861D1A831A330B" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. pinophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); 5) stipe usually vestured (but see 
<taxonomicName id="E78FC657F157A71B4F9F733D43FD21C4" genus="G." lsidName="G. glabrosipes" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="glabrosipes">
<emphasis id="50BE6DA4C74C1531C2010DDF091C532C" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. glabrosipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), usually appearing minutely barbed (30
<normalizedToken id="575581A7437486118DA70DDF23802E0A" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
); 6) lower stipe of dark, somber color, from dark sooty brown to virtually black; 6) rhizomorphs almost always present, always black, from &lt;2-40 
<normalizedToken id="723BF54FC99CF9D7380E7C45845B37D8" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2-0.7 mm, branched or unbranched; 7) basidiospores without significant dimension differences; 8) species apparently more or less host-specific, fruiting on dead conifer needles or rotting deciduous leafy debris; 9) pleurocystidia consistently present, fusiform, varying somewhat in distal morphology; 10) clamp connections ubiquitous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FB0EAE432A89DC2402C1D28948D016A5" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="comments">
<paragraph id="6344C07F70AA53C8143041BD9B6C378C" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Commentary.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="99A1C7F0334A0D25AADF7DCBA16A8982" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<normalizedToken id="D1942BDB1F75DF5F129F506E3EF6FC4B" originalValue="Antonín">Antonin</normalizedToken>
and Noordeloos (1997) recognized 
<taxonomicName id="91E337A3BC931FE5BD14E51620F5646E" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus subsp. subsect." order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="subSection" section="Vestipedes" species="glabrosipes" subSection="Impudicae" subSpecies="subsect.">Gymnopus sect. Vestipedes subsect. Impudicae</taxonomicName>
, including 
<taxonomicName id="02AF8C4A4D4B8B99ED143989E13F8009" genus="G." lsidName="G. perforans" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="perforans">
<emphasis id="B6E8A7B2724D01ADAEB4613382E25CB8" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. perforans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based, it would seem on the fetid odor of basidiomata of the included taxa. Later (
<bibRefCitation id="27B5014ABDFA489E2B67F345D14D664C" author="Antonin, V" journalOrPublisher="IHV-Verlag, Berlin" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" refId="B4" refString="Antonin, V, Noordeloos, ME, 2010. A monograph of Marasmioid and Collybioid fungi in Europe. IHV-Verlag, Berlin" title="A monograph of Marasmioid and Collybioid fungi in Europe." year="2010">
<normalizedToken id="14E00381FA5F0094DDD01FA753E792DD" originalValue="Antonín">Antonin</normalizedToken>
and Noordeloos 2010
</bibRefCitation>
), subsect. 
<taxonomicName id="40039621BA907090D70BFEA1B0C0D988" genus="G." lsidName="" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="subSection" subSection="Impudicae">
<emphasis id="F6B0362520EEA3F8DF2BBFB709E46E20" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Impudicae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was accepted at section rank, but basically included the same taxa as before. 
<bibRefCitation id="93C4B1D5638D2B4AD5F0330BFDF2096E" author="Wilson, AW" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="667 - 679" publicationUrl="10.3852/mycologia.97.3.667" refId="B41" refString="Wilson, AW, Desjardin, DE, 2005. Phylogenetic relationships in the gymnopoid and marasmioid fungi (Basidiomycetes, euagarics clade). Mycologia 97: 667 - 679, DOI: 10.3852/mycologia.97.3.667" title="Phylogenetic relationships in the gymnopoid and marasmioid fungi (Basidiomycetes, euagarics clade)." url="10.3852/mycologia.97.3.667" volume="97" year="2005">Wilson and Desjardin (2005)</bibRefCitation>
indicated that 
<taxonomicName id="D07F355B0B74FA90EFB210FBE92C8FD5" genus="G." lsidName="G. perforans" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="perforans">
<emphasis id="280273A041218D30D2E17E2EF4379174" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. perforans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
formed its own clade sister to that of 
<taxonomicName id="5CB07B892AB5F347EF2612E2815F7C52" genus="G." lsidName="G. (Micromphale) foetidum" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="foetidum" subGenus="Micromphale">G. (Micromphale) foetidum</taxonomicName>
and other mainstream odious 
<taxonomicName id="01AABCEB1C84A8F9927B441C329864FD" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus" order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="80BC8609158D52255292BEB5315F4389" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Gymnopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa. Based on the present study, the original 
<taxonomicName id="CFC43C950219A099840272FB341C2E2E" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Agaricaceae" genus="Micromphale" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Micromphale subsp. sect." order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="section" section="Perforantia" species="foetidum" subSpecies="sect.">Micromphale sect. Perforantia</taxonomicName>
is found to be more closely related to the 
<taxonomicName id="265AD0BCE3107A7B6796FCC8BB2DB777" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus (Marasmius) androsaceus" order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="androsaceus" subGenus="Marasmius">Gymnopus (Marasmius) androsaceus</taxonomicName>
complex, not inclusive of 
<taxonomicName id="75772643EA130CF7EAF0276C159ADD0E" genus="G." lsidName="G. foetidum" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species" species="foetidum">
<emphasis id="2817F2E4A039ED9717F706A9D85774DA" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G. foetidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other 
<taxonomicName id="E0616585DF493B6DAE7CCEB7F4B69311" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus subsp. sect." order="Agaricales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="section" section="Impudicae" species="foetidum" subSpecies="sect.">Gymnopus sect. Impudicae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B1FB25AA3AAE181F2E5F9B23DA7C1CD0" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
